The genus
Pseudione
has been regarded as the most primitive of the
Bopyridae (
Shiino 1965
)
, although this statement cannot apply to all currently included species as the genus is likely paraphyletic (
Adkison 1988
;
Boyko 2004 a
). The association of bopyrids and galatheids is very old, with evidence of host branchial chamber swellings found as far back as the Jurassic (
Markham 1986
) and galatheids may have been the original hosts for bopyrids among the Decapoda . It is worth noting that swellings on decapod carapaces can result from influences other than bopyrids (Boyko, personal observation), so it is unclear whether all fossilized swellings are caused by bopyrids because no actual fossilized bopyrids have been found, and the generic identities of fossil bopyrids remain unknown.
